description: In some senses, from inland +‎ -ish ("resembling or pertaining to an inland region"); in other senses, apparently from Middle English inlendisc (“native, indigenous”), from Old English inlendisċ; seemingly always to serve as an antonym to outlandish meaning "foreign, extravagant".

entries.meaning: (rare) Relating to or produced in the land itself, domestic, home, native.
(rare) Characteristic of one who is native or native-born; inexperienced, naïve, simplistic, unrefined.
Of or pertaining to the interior of a country; of an inland nature or character.
